(This file targets v0.9 provider grammar — Channel block with named
Action sub-blocks. Will not compile until Phase 4 lands. Use as a
worked spec example for `Action called "<name>"` always nested
inside a Channel.)

(Why named actions exist: a single chat-platform integration may need
several distinct verbs, each with its own audit posture, its own
authorization scope, and possibly its own deploy-config-bound target.
Without named actions, each verb would need its own Channel block
duplicating provider, auth, and lifecycle. Named actions let one
Channel ("incident bot") expose three distinct operations that share
the bot's identity but differ on everything else.

Who invokes the actions: NOT a compute calling them directly. Channel
actions are triggered by events — state transitions on Content,
events emitted by other Computes, or external webhook receipts. The
events come from the audit / state-machine layer; the channel action
sub-block is the destination side of a publish/subscribe. The example
below shows three event handlers, one per named action, demonstrating
the typical wiring.)

(Per-action targets: the deploy config can route different actions to
different chat targets without changing source. Channel-level config
sets the default target; per-action overrides nest under
config.actions.<action-name>:

  "channels": {
    "incident bot": {
      "provider": "slack",
      "config": {
        "workspace_token_ref": "${SLACK_BOT_TOKEN}",
        "target": "incidents-prod",
        "actions": {
          "page oncall": { "target": "pagers-prod" }
        }
      }
    }
  }
)

Application: Incident Bot
  Description: Posts incident lifecycle events to chat with three named actions: alert on creation, resolve on close, and page-oncall when severity escalates to critical.
Id: 3a8f2c19-6b04-4e72-9d51-7c8b1a2e6d40

Identity:
  Scopes are "incident.respond", "incident.manage", "incident.admin", and "incident.page"
  A "responder" has "incident.respond"
  A "manager" has "incident.respond" and "incident.manage"
  An "oncall captain" has "incident.respond", "incident.manage", "incident.admin", and "incident.page"

Content called "incidents":
  Each incident has a title which is text, required
  Each incident has a severity which is one of: "low", "medium", "high", "critical"
  Each incident has a lifecycle which is state:
    lifecycle starts as open
    lifecycle can also be acknowledged or resolved
    open can become acknowledged if the user has incident.respond
    acknowledged can become resolved if the user has incident.manage
  Each incident has an opened_at which is automatic
  Each incident has a resolved_at which is date and time
  Anyone with "incident.respond" can view incidents
  Anyone with "incident.manage" can create or update incidents
  Anyone with "incident.admin" can delete incidents

Channel called "incident bot":
  Provider is "messaging"
  Anyone with "incident.respond" can invoke this channel

  Action called "alert":
    Anyone with "incident.manage" can invoke this
    Takes incident : incident
    Send a message: `"🚨 [" + incident.severity + "] " + incident.title`

  Action called "resolve":
    Anyone with "incident.manage" can invoke this
    Takes incident : incident
    Send a message: `"✅ Resolved: " + incident.title + " — opened " + incident.opened_at`

  (Tighter scope than channel default — only oncall captains can page.
   The deploy config can also route THIS action to a different target
   (e.g., pagers-prod) without changing source.)
  Action called "page oncall":
    Anyone with "incident.page" can invoke this
    Takes incident : incident
    Send a message: `"📟 PAGE: " + incident.title + " — severity " + incident.severity`

(Event handlers that wire incident lifecycle to the channel actions.
This is where the actions actually get invoked. Each handler watches
for a specific state-machine transition or content event and
dispatches the appropriate named action.)

When an incident is created:
  Invoke channel action "alert" on "incident bot" with the new incident

When an incident lifecycle becomes resolved:
  Invoke channel action "resolve" on "incident bot" with the incident

When an incident severity becomes "critical":
  Invoke channel action "page oncall" on "incident bot" with the incident
